SilentPoet,No; "being" is used in many senses and ranges quite significantly depending on its context. There cannot be a better definition for God than Supreme Being. And, as you have probably noticed, it is certainly a common one. From the modifying qualifier, "Supreme" we can actually speculate on the majority of the properties of such a being. To put it simply, it means unrivalled and best. With regard to existence, such a being is that which exists necessarily; and, this tells us several things, once again. For example, that all that exists is contingent upon its existence; it can never be destroyed, etc...To your original question: "What is God?" People have various ideas of what "God" is, and they vary quite significantly. Some think there are a plethora of gods, some think there to be only one. I assume you are referring to the God of Classical Theism, however. Such a being has various attributes, and, I'm sure you know of them. So, just what is the point of this thread? See the Catholic's take on God. Not all people claim that God is undefinable; and, that is rather a sweeping claim.
