Heh, you've got an interesting definition of "all"; your "all" here seems to include that which does not exist. You probably don't see the absurdity in the presupposition, but I'll give you an analogy to show the problem:A scenario. We had a test in Math yesterday, and today, we got our test results. A friend of mine asks me, "how many marks did you get right on the test?" I reply, "I got all the marks right" (as if ;)). Now, surely, from this we would think that I got 100% on my test, but by your reasoning, I should have got something like oo%, since, "all" here should also--apparently--include that which is impossible. Of course, that never happens. We are not concerned with the impossible -- the impossible can never occur. Period. Maybe it's best to think of it in terms of Modal Logic, too. When using possible world semantics and we define ontological perfection as that which exists in all the possible worlds, we are not concerned, obviously, with the impossible worlds. Because, quite frankly, because they do not exist. Nevertheless, I'm interested by your presupposition that it is impossible for inaminate objects to be conscious. (i) What do you base this on? (ii) and how do you explain the miracle before your eyes, therefore.I think you've misunderstood the use of possible world semantics. For one, they patently don't only refer to the physical, but to everything, and neither do they make appeals to materialism and/or other types of monism/dualism. As they stand, they at least appear compatible with other metaphysical concepts as such. On another note, possible world semantics makes no such claim to presuppose anything along the lines of that these worlds exist. They are but a tool for understanding different parts of the modal family, in particular -- the popular S5. You seem to be appealing to materialism, however, which would of course pretty much eliminate the concept of a Supreme Being as is described, but lucky for us, materialism as I see it has major flaws. I'll outline them if you wish; just say. No worry there; just check out a little bit of Philosophy of Science; as I suggested, Popper is good, but maybe a little cryptic. Introductory books are normally good, however. Unfortunately not, and that is one of the problems with a definition as such for "evil". They're always either circular or just plain erroneous. Examples are fine and dandy, but definitions are required. Since you are positing that evil exists as one of your central premises, I want to know what you mean by it before I can agree that it exists; surely, that's reasonable, is it not? For thinking about evil, I like to consider some aspects of science and other things as such. For example, light and darkness. If you think about darkness, you'll find that it, itself, has no substance, but that it is only light that has substance. We see a lot of opposites in nature -- electrons and positrons, matter and anti-matter. But, there are those particles that do not have an opposite; for example, a photon is electrically neutral, just like the other force carriers: Z bosons and gluons. When something is light, we know that photons are coming from or being reflected of somethingn and then reaching our eye. Light is photons. However, for darkness, there is no other particle -- no particle that provides darkness. Darkness itself is merely the absence of light.Another parallel might be seen with coldness and heat. Heat comes about from energy, more specifically -- thermal energy. What we call "cold" is but an absence of heat (never a complete absence, since that would propose absolute zero on a Kelvin scale, which, theoretically, we never could really measure -- temperatures for us never get near that low). When we say that a person is "cold" we mean that they are lacking in emotion.And from these, I think it is the same with goodness. Goodness is that which exists and evil is merely the privation of it. It works this way and not the other way around because goodness is the aesthetic, in that case, it is that which morally edifies. Evil is merely the essence of moral emptiness. I think I've said a lot, and I wouldn't want to drag on and say a whole lot more; good luck with your computer and I hope it works out. Hey, when you get back, maybe we can get to the problem of good. ;)
